tool.name: FT2_Scale16to8BitSet

param.name: workspace
param.dialogReference:
Workspace. Root directory that contains the 'Mosaic' subdirectory where the "FT1_R2ReadOrthoMosaic" tool (run standalone or called by "FT0_FloodMaster") has placed polarized SAR images during the first step of producing a Flood Product. Script will create subdirectories 'Scaled', 'Scaled_Unfiltered' and 'Scratch', if they are not already present, and will transform the selected '16-Bit Polarized SAR Image' files from 16-bit to 8-bit, producing both filtered images in the 'Scaled' folder by applying a 3x3 rectangular median smoothing algorithm, and unfiltered images in the 'Scaled_Unfiltered' folder.

Example:

D:\Floods\QC_Richelieu\20110507_225926_F6F

param.name: sarImage16Bit
param.dialogReference:
16-bit Polarized Image(s). One or more 16-bit polarized images that were produced and placed in in the 'Mosaic' subdirectory by a preceding call tothe "FT1_R2ReadOrthoMosaic" tool. Field will be automatically populated when the 'Workspace' field is assigned a value. By default, the image selected for further processing will be for the HH polarization channel if it has been captured, or for the first polarization channel encountered otherwise. It is possible to choose any or all images for processing.

Example:

  • D:\Floods\QC_Richelieu\20110507_225926_F6F\Mosaic\20110507_225926_UTM18_mos_HH.tif

  • D:\Floods\QC_Richelieu\20110507_225926_F6F\Mosaic\20110507_225926_UTM18_mos_HV.tif

param.name: constrastStretch
param.expression: Min-Max Range | Min-90% Max Range | 95% Confidence Interval | 99% Confidence Interval
param.dialogReference:
Constrast Stretch. The algorithm to be applied to reduce 16-bit pixel values into 8-bit equivalents. Four different options are supported, all of which apply a linear stretch. Of the four, the first is the default, and the first two will likely be less troublesome:

Min-Max Range

The endpoints of the linear stretch will span across the entire range of pixel values found in the 16-bit image such that the minimum value will represent 1 and the maximum value will represent 255 in the 8-bit image. This option is the default. Values between the minimum and maximum will be distributed across the range using the following formula:

8BitValue = (((16BitValue - MinValue) / (MaxValue - MinValue)) * 255) + 0.5

Min-90% Max Range

Similar to "Min-Max Range" except that the linear stretch will run from the minimum value to 90% of the maximum value. Any 16-bit value that exceeds the 90% maximum will be assigned an 8-bit value of 255, resulting in a somewhat refined version of "Min-Max Range" with the lower 'water' end of the spectrum distributed across a wider spread. Values on the higher end will not be water anyway so can be discounted. If one examines the "Min-Max Range" data and finds that a threshold of 9 does not classify enough data as water and a value of 10 classifies too much, for example, he or she may find that a "Min-90% Max Range" value of 10 may be just right, appearing to be the rough equivalent of a "Min-Max Range" value of 9.5. Values between the will be distributed across the range using the following formula:Values between the minimum and 90% maximum will be distributed across the range using the following formula:

if 16BitValue < 90%MaxValue

8BitValue = (((16BitValue - MinValue) / (90%MaxValue - MinValue)) * 255) + 0.5

else

8BitValue = 255

95% Confidence Interval

The endpoints for this linear stretch option equal the Mean ± 1.96 Standard Deviations. The data distribution and resultant spread of the normal curve will establish how the 16-bit pixel values are treated. If a 16-bit pixel value is smaller than the lower bound of the confidence interval, then it will be assigned an 8-bit value of 1. Similarly, if a 16-bit pixel value is larger than the upper bound of the confidence interval, then it will be assigned an 8-bit value of 1. Values in between the lower and upper bound will be prorated in a similar manner as the previous two options.

A problem arises when the spread of the normal curve is wider than the data, causing the lower bound of the confidence interval to be less than that of the smallest actual pixel value, often negative. In that case, the lower and upper bounds will be corrected by shifting the enpoints to the right by an amount equal to the difference between the lower bound and the smallest actual pixel value. This will ensure the smallest 8-bit value will be 1 rather than something larger like 30, making water thresholding in the "FT3_ExtractFloodExtentAndConvertToVector" tool function much the same as it does for the other options.

Values between the lower and upper confidence interval bounds will be distributed across the range using the following formula:

if LowerConfInt < MinValue

delta = MinValue - LowerConfInt

LowerConfInt = LowerConfInt + delta

UpperConfInt = UpperConfInt + delta

if 16BitValue <= LowerConfInt

8BitValue = 1

else if 16BitValue >= LowerConfInt

8BitValue = 255

else

8BitValue = (((16BitValue - LowerConfInt) / (UpperConfInt - LowerConfInt)) * 255) + 0.5

99% Confidence Interval

Identical to the "95% Confidence Interval" option except that the endpoints equal the Mean ± 2.5 Standard Deviations.

tool.summary:
Second tool employed in the procedure to generate Flood Products. Can be run standalone, however is also executed by the "FT0_FloodMaster" tool.

May be run standalone after examining the initial results from "FT0_FloodMaster" if the polarization channel originally chosen has not generated an acceptable product and an alternate channel is to be tried (it is not necessary to rerun "FT0_FloodMaster" from scratch in that circumstance, nor "FT1_R2ReadOrthoMosaic" for that matter; can use the files placed in the 'Mosaic' subdirectory by those tools as a starting point).

Starting in the workspace root directory, creates all subdirectories it requires if they are not already present ('Scaled', 'Scaled_Unfiltered', 'Scratch'), then processes one or more polarized image files (HH, HV, VV, VH), selected from those that were produced by the "FT1_R2ReadOrthoMosaic" tool and placed in the 'Mosaic' subdirectory. Processing includes transforming from 16-bit to 8-bit, and applying a 3x3 rectangular median filter to smooth the results in an attempt to reduce the speckle noise, thereby reducing the number of 'holes' and associated polygons that will be generated by the third tool in the procedure("FT3_ExtractFloodExtentAndConvertToVector").

The background of images created will be set to 0 instead of NoData since this is required for webserver display. The filtered images will be used for the flood extraction process, while the unfiltered images may be more suitable for webserver display when the SAR image has been capture in Standard beam mode (in Fine beam mode, filtering may produce a better result).

Since all of the geoprocessing functions used in this tool are part of the ArcGIS libraryand hence 32-bit, it is not necessary for the tool to run in background mode. As a consequence, when run standalone, the "Results" window will be open and run in the foreground. It supports both a GUI and command-line interface, the latter useful for incorporating it within a larger batch script.

Example:

The filename format for files created by this tool and written to the 'Scaled' subdirectory is:

YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS_PROJECTION_mos_POLARIZATION_8bit_MED3x3.tif

Files similar to the following would be produced for a SAR image that has captured both HH and HV polarization channels.

  • 20110522_110144_UTM18_mos_HH_8bit_MED3x3.tif

  • 20110522_110144_UTM18_mos_HV_8bit_MED3x3.tif
tool.usage:
Command Line Call:

FT2_Scale16to8BitSet.py [-h] -img16 IMAGE16BIT -ws WORKSPACE

- OR -

FT2_Scale16to8BitSet.py [-h] --image16bit IMAGE16BIT --workspace WORKSPACE

- OR -

a blend of the above flags.
